1. Software Bugs and Configuration Issues:
  DLL-Related Bugs: There have been instances where DLLs, such as libifcoremd.dll, have caused applications to abort upon receiving a Ctrl+C event.
    For example, a user reported a forrtl: error (200) when using PyMC3 in Visual Studio Code, indicating a runtime failure linked to DLL handling of Ctrl+C signals .â€‹PyMC Discourse

  Console Applications: In some cases, console applications fail to handle Ctrl+C correctly due to improper configuration of control handlers. For instance, using SetConsoleCtrlHandler improperly can lead to the application ignoring Ctrl+C inputs .â€‹Stack Overflow+1DEV Community+1

  Development Environment Issues: Certain development environments, like Visual Studio, have been reported to interfere with Ctrl+C functionality in child processes. This is often due to inherited settings that disable Ctrl+C handling .â€‹

2. Third-Party Software Conflicts:
Global Hotkey Interception: Applications or scripts that set global hotkeys can intercept Ctrl+C, preventing it from reaching its intended target. For example, AutoHotKey scripts have been known to cause such issues .â€‹Stack Overflow

  Clipboard Managers: Some clipboard management tools can interfere with standard copy-paste operations, leading to Ctrl+C failures. Disabling or uninstalling these tools often resolves the issue .â€‹GeeksforGeeks

3. Driver and System-Level Issues:
Keyboard Drivers: Outdated or corrupted keyboard drivers can cause Ctrl+C to stop working. Updating the drivers through Device Manager has been a recommended solution .â€‹GeeksforGeeks+1TECHCOMMUNITY.MICROSOFT.COM+1

  System Updates: Missing or pending Windows updates can also lead to unexpected behavior with keyboard shortcuts. Ensuring the system is up-to-date is a common troubleshooting step .â€‹GeeksforGeeks

